Tantalizing titles aside, progesterone is also produced in men as part of testicular and adreanl synthesis of testosterone and other androgens, so it is not strictly a female "sex" hormone. The additional, intriguing, untold story here is that progesterone is also produced by the Schwann cells of the peripheral nerve cells to aid in myelin production (the nerve lining) as well as the glia cells of the brain and central nervous system. Like the article briefly states, there is substantial evidence that progesterone plays a central role in the pathway of repair and neurogenesis.
As to how this is "dirty" drug, is more telling of the speakers perspective, than a helpful adjective. In most ways I believe he is referring it's lack of specificity and unknown effects.
Sexy and dirty have been partner words for many folks, especially in the past. Neither are helpful nor accurate descriptors here. I would expect a bit better for science mag.

