Brain Observatory
With their presentations at AAAS, Drs. Marino and Weiss brought ethical issues on treatment of cetaceans to the foreground. They were passionate and outspoken about their views on captivity and exploitation of cetaceans from the perspective of serious professionals who admire and study their brain and cognitive abilities. Mixing science with policy is tricky because it is easy to lose track of which one drives the other, but the session undoubtedly stimulated interest from the public - which is good and necessary. Research on cetaceans is extremely problematic. Direct physiological mapping of brain functions on these animals was forsaken in the 70s (fortunately), but recent non-invasive imaging research could shed some light on dolphin cognition. However, paradoxically, this and new anatomical studies would be impossible if some of these animals were not living in captivity. One thing is certain, new data is needed to substantiate the claim that a dolphin is a 'person' and what better incentive than preservation. Are funding agencies listening? Jacopo Annese, The Brain Observatory, UCSD. http://thebrainobservatory.ucsd.edu/
