tadchem
"The idea is that when shrubs and trees invade former grazing lands, they soak up so much groundwater that streams slow down and water supplies to cities and towns decrease." This is patently absurd. Stream water, which becomes river water and refills reservoirs, is a function of *rainwater* runoff, not groundwater. Extensive root systems from brush and trees prevent the formation of hard-pan and calich, allowing the rainwater to percolate into the ground instead of running off. This is a case of the 'conventional wisdom' being dead wrong. The real drivers for aquifer recharging are the decadal and multi-decadal climate oscillations - the PDO, AMO, NAO, and the 11-year solar activity cycle.

