VS Ramachandran
Mr Enserink's otherwise balanced report fails to mention a compromise suggestion I brought up during my conversation with him. I suggested that the journal continue its old policy of publishing ALL articles so long as they meet minimum standards as set by the board of editors. However each paper should also be peer reviewed in the ordinary fashion with the outside referee being told he/she is not allowed to recommend rejection. Their comments - whether critical or flattering - will then be posted on the MEDICAL HYPOTHESES WEB site in parallel - or shortly after - the print edition. (These could be published anonymous or signed as per referees request.) This system will ensure that highly speculative and creative ideas get the exposure they deserve AND at the same time ensure that people don't expose themselves by publishing rubbish, whose 'holes' are exposed simultaneously. This is important because there is currently NO other journal whose main agenda is to publish speculative IDEAS for others to ponder over. In my opinion the danger of good ideas being trashed prematurely outweighs the danger of cluttering the literature with nonsense. (This argument can't be applied to AIDS where lives are involved; I have no expertise to comment on that particular debate.)
VS Ramachandran MD PhD Director and distinguished professor Center for brain and cognition, UCSD

