If you are in the sciences, you know that a HYPOTHESIS is just that; it does not imply that the theory is proven. It seems clear that we need a place for ideas that are controversial can be aired. I disagree with firing Bruce Charlton; it seems to me that he is producing exactly the journal that Medical Hypotheses should be. Surely, if Elsevier has problems, it would be better to title the journal "Controversial Medical Hypotheses" than to fire the editor who seems to be doing his job well.
It seems to me that had this journal existed far enough back, it would have been the first to publish the idea that hand washing might be a good idea to prevent patient death by infection. Don't we want to keep such a journal that publishes new, strange, even radical ideas, and keep the editor who chooses that sort of possibly outlandish article?

