If there is a problem with a journal like "Medical Hypotheses" it is that one person decides which articles to publish--by definition, that produces bias. But radical/thought-provoking/unpopular ideas need legitimate venues in which to be expressed, or we risk stifling something far more valuable than freedom of speech: freedom of thought. Everyone has a range of thoughts and ideas, including many that are inappropriate. Healthy individuals choose which ideas to incorporate into a belief system by expressing and defending their thoughts, and watching others do the same. Without this process, ideas exist only in our heads, where over time they can become increasingly romanticized and sundered from reality. Journals like "Medical Hypotheses," however, have a duty to candidly inform readers that the articles they publish are not peer-reviewed and do not represent mainstream scientific consensus. If a journal honestly meets that burden, then the public is free to make informed choices about what to believe.

